1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
Hey everybody. My name is Dane Frederiksen.
I am a B2B video expert,

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:09,000
and I'm here today with Todd Fairbairn,
who is from Emotiv Mobility,

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:13,000
and we're here to talk about what's going on
in this crazy world of marketing and AI

4
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:17,000
and all the things we need to be thinking
about right now.

5
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Todd, why don't you introduce yourself and
tell us a little bit about what we need to know about you.

6
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:25,000
Dane, thank you so much for having me on.
Todd Fairbairn —

7
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:29,000
I am Head of Marketing and Brand
at Emotiv Mobility.

8
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:34,000
It's a really interesting time to be in our space.
B2B marketing is always a challenge.

9
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:38,000
You've got to cut through the noise.
But I think you throw in AI

10
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:42,000
and everything that's happening,
and for brand folks on usually smaller teams,

11
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:46,000
you've got to leverage AI.
But how do you do it in a way that's authentic,

12
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:50,000
true to the brand, and isn't just slop?
It's a great tool,

13
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:54,000
but you've got to be responsible with it.

14
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:59,000
It's such a great moment to be having
this conversation. AI just took all the air

15
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:04,000
out of the room. We all went nuts last year,
made all this slop —

16
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,000
word of the year. Now I'm seeing the pendulum
swing back the other way.

17
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:12,000
They're hiring content writers to be human again.
There's finally some appreciation

18
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:17,000
for the work that we do, and it has real value
beyond just hitting numbers with volume.

19
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:22,000
So when that meets actual practice —
how are you using AI, or not using it?

20
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:25,000
What's top of mind for you?

21
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:30,000
We use it a fair bit, in full transparency.
It's not our North Star,

22
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:34,000
nor does it help us get there. But we use it
to gut check a lot of our activities.

23
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:39,000
My marketing team — we're a smaller B2B
in the automotive space.

24
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:44,000
It's myself, I have a marketing performance
and operations manager who leads our campaigns,

25
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:48,000
and then I have a content creator
who's diving into the material.

26
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:53,000
AI for us — we use it for keeping our website
content fresh, looking at what others

27
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:57,000
in the space are doing, and guiding us
on blog posts, thinking about keywords.

28
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:02,000
We'd love to see how we can use tools
from a video content perspective.

29
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:06,000
That is real intriguing for a smaller group.
How can we get more with less?

30
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:11,000
But then use it with the diligence
and responsibility of remaining true to the brand.

31
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:16,000
This is one of my goals with this interview series —
to take the chocolate and the peanut butter

32
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:20,000
and put them together. Me as a video expert,
you as a marketer with your expertise.

33
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:25,000
I'm always advocating for leveraging video
in an authentic way that still lets you

34
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:29,000
use AI responsibly without diluting your brand.

35
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:34,000
I think the best term for it is
video-first content marketing.

36
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:39,000
The idea is that video, because it contains
all other formats, is the perfect raw ingredient

37
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:43,000
for a content system that's repeatable
and ongoing.

38
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:48,000
Imagine an interview like this chopped up
into shorts, take the transcript,

39
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:52,000
use that for written content. If you plan that
ahead of time rather than repurposing

40
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:56,000
as an afterthought — I call it pre-purposing.

41
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:01,000
Planning ahead, building a system
that's low-lift.

42
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:06,000
SMEs shouldn't be writing articles,
especially in this day and age.

43
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:10,000
An interview like this is a great way
to extract on-brand thought leadership

44
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:14,000
and repurpose it across all channels.

45
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:19,000
There's this idea that so many different levels
of quality are acceptable now.

46
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:24,000
A scrappy iPhone video or a webcam video
like this has value if the content is valuable

47
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:28,000
and it's used in the right way, in the right place.

48
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:33,000
Of course, polished brand videos
and Super Bowl commercials have their place too.

49
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:37,000
But post-pandemic, social media world —
there's this other lane

50
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:41,000
that B2B is just now waking up to.

51
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:46,000
I love where your head's at, Dane.
Sometimes you never have enough time

52
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:50,000
to tackle these ideas.
From your perspective, it's almost like

53
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:55,000
a grand campaign where you have longer form
content and you break it down

54
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:59,000
and leverage it across a multitude
of different facets.

55
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:04,000
That was a big driving principle
while I was at Ford Motor Company.

56
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:09,000
And what I think is so fun — for so long,
B2B has been kind of rigid, no personality.

57
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:14,000
There's a hesitancy for brands to step out
and be their own identity.

58
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:18,000
There's a lot of hiding. It's the people,
the humanity, that makes a huge impact

59
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:22,000
as a brand differentiator.

60
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:27,000
It's one of the things we've been looking at doing.
How might we get the individuals

61
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:32,000
on an assembly line at one of our facilities
to capture the actual pieces coming together —

62
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:37,000
an activity that 99% of people
wouldn't normally see.

63
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:42,000
But there are so many supply chain companies
touching that product. It's really cool moments.

64
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:47,000
The biggest opportunity for brands in our space
is to flex about the people doing the work.

65
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:52,000
Everyone's sitting on a content goldmine,
because you do have the subject matter experts,

66
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:57,000
the people doing the work. There's this idea
of hiding behind white papers and ghost writing.

67
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:02,000
The marketplace has started to demand
something different.

68
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:07,000
A lot of execs are being asked to take off
the mask and be real. And it makes people uncomfortable.

69
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:12,000
So what I'm getting closer to now is finding ways
people can say yes.

70
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:17,000
The grand master plan content strategy
just sounds too big, too hard.

71
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:22,000
How can we start small?
Let's give this a pilot project name.

72
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:27,000
Let's call this a test. Making it so the bar
is low and you can get some reps in.

73
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:32,000
A lot of people don't want to be on camera.
If you can make that less scary —

74
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:37,000
let's just record something and not post it.
We'll look at it, talk about it,

75
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:41,000
and then maybe take another swing.

76
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:46,000
I think there are paths forward
in either direction.

77
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:51,000
The beauty of my job is I get to try
different things.

78
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:55,000
People in my space haven't done it before.
Doesn't mean it's wrong.

79
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:59,000
Doesn't mean it's right. You don't really know
until you give it a whirl.

80
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:04,000
Making this part of some grandiose annual
strategic marketing plan —

81
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:08,000
that just sounds daunting and not fun.

82
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:13,000
Everybody in marketing, we're in it to build
things we love to see.

83
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:18,000
I love incremental approaches.
Let's try this.

84
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:23,000
We flirted with the idea of TikTok
while at CES. That was interesting.

85
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:28,000
When we were at CES, that's where the audience was.
It would be prudent to be there.

86
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:33,000
You have to give things the opportunity
before you automatically dismiss them.

87
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:38,000
Everything we've known has kind of flipped
on its head in the past 10 years.

88
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:42,000
That's the beauty and the frustration
of our space.

89
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:47,000
How are you selling this "we've got to just
try it" mentality to people who need ROI,

90
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:51,000
numbers, results? How do you balance the need
to measure with the need to test?

91
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:56,000
It is a balancing act,
and that's the most stressful part.

92
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:01,000
We'll do little pilot-type programs where it's
a piece of a smaller underlying budget.

93
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:06,000
We let the core piece of the business
carry the mail, then we see what kind of reaction

94
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:10,000
these little pilots cause.

95
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:15,000
If you string a couple together
over a couple of quarters,

96
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:19,000
then you might be on to something.
Then it's easier to convince leadership

97
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:24,000
that this is something we try
a little bit more in subsequent years.

98
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:29,000
It's these incremental, anecdotal tries
to see where we might connect.

99
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:33,000
If we're on to something,
then we keep pushing until we crack the egg

100
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:37,000
or start from scratch.

101
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:42,000
As you're looking forward — what are the things
in front of you? What's the next thing

102
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:46,000
for you, or for the industry?
Where are we headed?

103
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:51,000
I think AI, in terms of being able
to harness it — one of my marketing leads

104
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:56,000
has been all over Claude for the past
couple of weeks, figuring out how to leverage it

105
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:00,000
better for what we're doing.

106
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:05,000
I do think there's going to continue to be
a movement to have people telling the story,

107
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:10,000
focusing on individuals to write copy,
because there are differences.

108
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:14,000
You can tell things are AI-written
versus an actual individual.

109
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:19,000
That delicate balance will continue to be there.

110
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:24,000
It's been a wild 12 months.
It's probably going to be a wild 24 months

111
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:28,000
as these tools continue to get smarter.

112
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:33,000
We as marketers have a responsibility
to be good stewards of the tools,

113
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:37,000
leverage them in a way that's beneficial
for our craft.

114
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:42,000
Whether it's HubSpot or other platforms
pushing AI functionality —

115
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:46,000
you're just inundated with AI everywhere.
That'll be fascinating to see

116
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:50,000
how these capabilities all connect
and intertwine.

117
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:54,000
It's the wild west all over again.
Todd, thanks for joining me today.

118
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:58,000
Great conversation.
Good luck out there.

119
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:02,000
Absolutely. Dane, appreciate the time. Cheers.
